We differentiate $x^{3}$ repeatedly and antidifferentiate $e^{2x}$ repeatedly:

| Sign | Derivatives of $x^{3}$ | Antiderivatives of $e^{2x}$ |
| $+$ | $x^{3}$ | $\tfrac{1}{2}e^{2x}$ |
| $-$ | $3x^{2}$ | $\tfrac{1}{4}e^{2x}$ |
| $+$ | $6x$ | $\tfrac{1}{8}e^{2x}$ |
| $-$ | $6$ | $\tfrac{1}{16}e^{2x}$ |
| $0$ |

Reading off the diagonal products:
$$
 \int x^{3}\,e^{2x}\dx
 &= (+)\,x^{3}\cdot\tfrac{1}{2}e^{2x}
 + (-)\,3x^{2}\cdot\tfrac{1}{4}e^{2x}
 + (+)\,6x\cdot\tfrac{1}{8}e^{2x}
 + (-)\,6\cdot\tfrac{1}{16}e^{2x} + C \\[4pt]
 &= e^{2x}\!\left(\frac{x^{3}}{2}
 - \frac{3x^{2}}{4}
 + \frac{6x}{8}
 - \frac{6}{16}\right) + C \\[4pt]
 &= e^{2x}\!\left(\frac{x^{3}}{2}
 - \frac{3x^{2}}{4}
 + \frac{3x}{4}
 - \frac{3}{8}\right) + C.
$$
